{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"64fd9fcc-2a43-496c-ae05-0eec1fa36533","content":"Analyzing .dmp files is outside what I can automate here, but here are your best options:\n\n**`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\nUseful SOS commands inside the analyzer:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stacks\n- `pe` — print last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n- `threads` — list all threads\n\n**Visual Studio** (Windows):\nOpen the `.dmp` file directly — it provides a rich UI for inspecting threads, exceptions, and memory.\n\n**WinDbg / lldb**:\nFor deeper native + managed debugging with the SOS extension.\n\nWould you like help setting up any of these tools, or do you need to **collect** a new dump from a running/crashing process?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8a39bc6e-9c79-4c19-94a3-542fab01555b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\" So that skill is not appropriate here.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing crash dumps.","outputTokens":313},"id":"03268729-7196-4f48-9bca-49481690f05c","timestamp":"2026-04-03T01:05:55.541Z","parentId":"22f9d745-e008-47b8-9cf9-9b0803c78fe0"}
